            'scholarship requirements' => 'Scholarship requirements vary by type and sponsor, but common criteria include:\n\nAcademic Requirements:\nâ€¢ Minimum GPA: 2.5-4.0 (varies by scholarship)\nâ€¢ Standardized tests: SAT/ACT, GRE/GMAT, IELTS/TOEFL\nâ€¢ Academic transcripts from previous institutions\n\nPersonal Requirements:\nâ€¢ Personal statement or essays\nâ€¢ Letters of recommendation (2-3)\nâ€¢ Resume/CV highlighting achievements\nâ€¢ Leadership and extracurricular activities\n\nAdditional Requirements:\nâ€¢ Financial documents (for need-based)\nâ€¢ Research proposals (for research scholarships)\nâ€¢ Portfolio (for arts scholarships)\nâ€¢ Citizenship/residency proof\n\nTips: Research each scholarship\'s specific requirements and prepare documents in advance.',
            'how to get scholarship' => 'Increasing your scholarship chances requires strategy and preparation.\n\nAcademic Excellence:\nâ€¢ Maintain high GPA throughout studies\nâ€¢ Excel in standardized tests\nâ€¢ Take challenging courses\n\nStrong Application:\nâ€¢ Write compelling personal statements\nâ€¢ Secure excellent recommendations\nâ€¢ Highlight leadership and achievements\n\nStrategic Approach:\nâ€¢ Apply to multiple scholarships\nâ€¢ Start applications early\nâ€¢ Research thoroughly\nâ€¢ Meet all deadlines\nâ€¢ Follow up on applications\n\nAdditional Tips:\nâ€¢ Network with scholarship recipients\nâ€¢ Consider less competitive scholarships\nâ€¢ Apply for local and international awards\nâ€¢ Don\'t get discouraged by rejections\n\nSuccess Rate: Most students receive at least one scholarship with persistent effort.',
            'scholarship amount' => 'Scholarship amounts vary widely based on the sponsor and type.\n\nAmount Ranges:\nâ€¢ Small awards: $500-$2,000/year\nâ€¢ Medium awards: $2,000-$10,000/year\nâ€¢ Large awards: $10,000-$25,000/year\nâ€¢ Major awards: $25,000+/year\nâ€¢ Full coverage: $30,000-$60,000+/year (includes living expenses)\n\nCoverage Types:\nâ€¢ Tuition only\nâ€¢ Tuition + living expenses\nâ€¢ Tuition + books + supplies\nâ€¢ Stipends for research/teaching\n\nFactors Affecting Amount:\nâ€¢ Academic merit\nâ€¢ Financial need\nâ€¢ Field of study\nâ€¢ University prestige\nâ€¢ Country of origin\n\nStrategy: Combine multiple scholarships to maximize coverage.',
            'international scholarship' => 'International students have access to numerous scholarship opportunities.\n\nPopular Programs:\nâ€¢ DAAD (Germany) - Full funding for German studies\nâ€¢ Chevening (UK) - Leadership development scholarships\nâ€¢ Commonwealth Scholarships - For Commonwealth countries\nâ€¢ Erasmus+ (Europe) - EU-wide mobility program\nâ€¢ Australia Awards - Full scholarships for Australian study\nâ€¢ New Zealand Scholarships - Government-funded awards\n\nEligibility:\nâ€¢ Citizenship of eligible countries\nâ€¢ Academic excellence\nâ€¢ Leadership potential\nâ€¢ Commitment to development goals\n\nApplication Process:\nâ€¢ Country-specific applications\nâ€¢ Competitive selection process\nâ€¢ Interviews and assessments\n\nTips: Check your country\'s eligibility and apply through official channels.',
            'government scholarship' => 'Government-funded scholarships offer comprehensive support for international students.\n\nMajor Programs:\nâ€¢ Chevening Scholarships (UK) - For master\'s studies\nâ€¢ DAAD Scholarships (Germany) - Research and study awards\nâ€¢ Erasmus+ (European Union) - Mobility and cooperation\nâ€¢ Australia Awards - Development-focused scholarships\nâ€¢ Canadian Government Scholarships - Various programs\nâ€¢ US Government Programs - Through State Department\n\nBenefits:\nâ€¢ Full tuition coverage\nâ€¢ Living expenses stipends\nâ€¢ Health insurance\nâ€¢ Travel costs\nâ€¢ Academic and cultural support\n\nEligibility:\nâ€¢ Academic merit\nâ€¢ Leadership potential\nâ€¢ Development impact\nâ€¢ Language proficiency\n\nApplication: Highly competitive with early deadlines.',
            'university scholarship' => 'Most universities offer their own scholarship programs for international students.\n\nTypes:\nâ€¢ Admission-based scholarships (automatic with offer)\nâ€¢ Merit scholarships (separate application)\nâ€¢ Departmental scholarships (field-specific)\nâ€¢ Alumni scholarships (for alumni children)\nâ€¢ Athletic scholarships (sports performance)\nâ€¢ Research scholarships (graduate level)\n\nPopular University Scholarships:\nâ€¢ Harvard University Scholarships\nâ€¢ Stanford University Awards\nâ€¢ University of Toronto Scholarships\nâ€¢ University of Melbourne Awards\nâ€¢ ETH Zurich Excellence Scholarships\n\nApplication Process:\nâ€¢ Some automatic with admission\nâ€¢ Others require separate application\nâ€¢ Deadlines vary by university\n\nTips: Check university websites and apply early.',
            'sports scholarship' => 'Sports scholarships reward athletic talent and academic achievement.\n\nAvailable In:\nâ€¢ USA (NCAA Division I universities)\nâ€¢ Canada (CIS universities)\nâ€¢ UK (BUCS system)\nâ€¢ Australia (University sports programs)\n\nRequirements:\nâ€¢ Athletic excellence in your sport\nâ€¢ Academic qualifications (GPA 2.5+)\nâ€¢ Team fit and recruitment potential\nâ€¢ Sometimes tryouts or recruitment camps\n\nCoverage:\nâ€¢ Full or partial tuition\nâ€¢ Living expenses\nâ€¢ Training and equipment costs\nâ€¢ Academic support\n\nApplication Process:\nâ€¢ Contact university athletic departments\nâ€¢ Attend recruitment events\nâ€¢ Submit athletic and academic credentials\nâ€¢ May require video submissions\n\nTips: Start early, maintain academic eligibility, and consider walk-on opportunities.',
            'research scholarship' => 'Research scholarships support graduate students conducting research.\n\nTypes:\nâ€¢ University research assistantships\nâ€¢ Government research grants\nâ€¢ Private foundation fellowships\nâ€¢ Industry-sponsored research awards\n\nBenefits:\nâ€¢ Tuition waivers\nâ€¢ Monthly stipends ($1,000-$3,000)\nâ€¢ Research funding\nâ€¢ Conference travel support\nâ€¢ Health insurance\n\nEligibility:\nâ€¢ Admission to graduate program\nâ€¢ Research proposal\nâ€¢ Faculty supervisor support\nâ€¢ Academic excellence\n\nFields: STEM, Social Sciences, Humanities\n\nApplication: Through graduate admissions or separate research applications.\n\nTips: Identify research interests early and build relationships with potential supervisors.',
            'women scholarship' => 'Women-specific scholarships promote gender equality in education.\n\nOrganizations:\nâ€¢ AAUW International Fellowships\nâ€¢ Zonta International\nâ€¢ Women in STEM scholarships\nâ€¢ Leadership and business scholarships\nâ€¢ Country-specific women\'s programs\n\nFocus Areas:\nâ€¢ STEM fields\nâ€¢ Business and leadership\nâ€¢ Social sciences\nâ€¢ Arts and humanities\nâ€¢ Developing country students\n\nBenefits:\nâ€¢ Tuition coverage\nâ€¢ Living expenses\nâ€¢ Leadership development\nâ€¢ Networking opportunities\n\nEligibility:\nâ€¢ Female gender\nâ€¢ Academic merit\nâ€¢ Leadership potential\nâ€¢ Commitment to women\'s advancement\n\nTips: Highlight leadership and community involvement in applications.',
            'minority scholarship' => 'Minority scholarships support underrepresented and disadvantaged groups.\n\nGroups Served:\nâ€¢ Ethnic minorities\nâ€¢ LGBTQ+ students\nâ€¢ Students with disabilities\nâ€¢ First-generation students\nâ€¢ Refugees and displaced persons\nâ€¢ Indigenous students\n\nOrganizations:\nâ€¢ UNCF (United Negro College Fund)\nâ€¢ Hispanic Scholarship Fund\nâ€¢ Asian American scholarships\nâ€¢ Native American programs\nâ€¢ Disability-specific awards\n\nCoverage:\nâ€¢ Tuition assistance\nâ€¢ Living expenses\nâ€¢ Academic support\nâ€¢ Career development\n\nApplication: Demonstrate how your background and experiences align with scholarship goals.\n\nTips: Research culturally-specific scholarships and highlight unique perspectives.',
            'study abroad scholarship' => 'Study abroad scholarships specifically fund international education experiences.\n\nTypes:\nâ€¢ Cultural exchange programs\nâ€¢ Bilateral government agreements\nâ€¢ University study abroad offices\nâ€¢ Private foundation awards\nâ€¢ Short-term exchange scholarships\n\nPrograms:\nâ€¢ Erasmus+ (Europe)\nâ€¢ Gilman Scholarship (USA)\nâ€¢ DAAD (Germany)\nâ€¢ Australia\'s New Colombo Plan\nâ€¢ Canada\'s International Scholarships\n\nBenefits:\nâ€¢ Program fees\nâ€¢ Travel costs\nâ€¢ Living expenses\nâ€¢ Cultural immersion activities\n\nEligibility:\nâ€¢ Enrollment in home institution\nâ€¢ Academic standing\nâ€¢ Language proficiency\nâ€¢ Cultural interest\n\nTips: Check with your university\'s study abroad office for opportunities.',
            'financial aid' => 'Financial aid encompasses various funding sources beyond scholarships.\n\nOptions:\nâ€¢ Scholarships and grants (need not repay)\nâ€¢ Work-study programs (part-time jobs)\nâ€¢ Student loans (must repay with interest)\nâ€¢ Assistantships (teaching/research)\nâ€¢ Emergency funds\n\nSources:\nâ€¢ University financial aid offices\nâ€¢ Government student aid programs\nâ€¢ Private lenders\nâ€¢ Nonprofit organizations\n\nApplication:\nâ€¢ FAFSA or equivalent forms\nâ€¢ Demonstrate financial need\nâ€¢ Provide documentation\n\nTips: Compare aid packages, understand repayment terms, and explore all options before borrowing.',
            'funding' => 'Comprehensive funding strategies for international students.\n\nSources:\nâ€¢ University scholarships (30-50% coverage)\nâ€¢ Government grants and scholarships\nâ€¢ Private foundation awards\nâ€¢ Personal savings and family support\nâ€¢ Part-time work opportunities\nâ€¢ Student loans (as last resort)\n\nAverage Coverage: 30-70% of total costs through various sources.\n\nStrategy:\n1. Apply for multiple scholarships\n2. Seek university funding\n3. Consider work opportunities\n4. Plan budget carefully\n5. Look for emergency funds\n\nTips: Start planning 12-18 months before study start and track all funding sources.',

